\begin_layout Standard
Bushfires produce massive impacts in Australia.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Haynes2010"

\end_inset

 categorised them as the fourth most lethal natural hazard in this country.
 Several catastrophic events have contributed to this ranking.
 For example, the “Black Saturday” fires produced 173 fatalities in February
 of 2009 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Teague2010"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, bushfires not only threaten life but also impact the Australian
 economy.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "McAneney2009"

\end_inset

 reports that bushfires are responsible for 20% of property losses in Australia.
 In fact, only the costs of the "Ash Wednesday" fires of 1983 reached $1.63
 billion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, there is evidence sugggesting that future bushfires could
 become more dangerous in several regions of Australia.
 The south-east of the continent might experience greater risk.
 For example, days with “very high” and “extreme” fire danger would become
 more common 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lucas2007"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Clarke2011"

\end_inset

 argues that future fire seasons could start earlier and be more prolonged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In southeastern Australia, the state of Victoria is one the most bushfire
 prone and vulnerable areas.
 This region endured the most catastrophic bushfire events in Australian
 history (e.g.
 "Black Friday" 1939, "Ash Wednesday" 1983, "Black Saturday" 2009).
 Additionally, half of the economic impacts in Australia occurred in Victoria
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Luke1978"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, climate projections also suggest its fire danger risk will
 increase 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clarke2011"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, Victoria is a region where preparedness for fire seasons is
 of utmost importance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently, the state of Victoria in Australia uses a qualitative approach
 to make seasonal bushfire forecasts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 These forecasts are based on antecedent conditions of maximum temperature,
 soil moisture, vegetation density and the phase of climate modes of varaibility
 such as El Nino Southern Oscillation (ENSO).
 Additionally, the estimation is also complemented with the outlook of climate
 variables such as maximun and minimum temperature as well as precipitation.
 Worldwide, the application of statistical seasonal forecasting schemes
 to predict similar climate-related natural hazards such as floods and droughts
 has been demonstrated to be viable and in continous improvement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murphy2001"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

